			<p>
				I sent out an e-mail with a subject line of "[msr.sigcf] proxy configurator" and a body with an MD5 of <i>ccaa13b3af167a1b01f14e29e52dc7b3</i>, which has an HTML version with an MD5 of <i>bf2cb5d7acaa7881f53cc4d0c9abfe41</i>.
				I sent it on Tuesday, December 10, 2019 at 11:29:49 CST (<i>i.e.</i>, -0600) or 1575998989 seconds or /calendar/Gregorian/AD/2019/12/10/17/29/49 .
			</p>
		</section>
		<section>
			<p>
				In my previous e-mail, I neglected to mention that an echo server is a pretty dangerous thing to have lying around, as anyone can ask it to send any JS to the page, and that JS will appear to come from the echo server.
				It's really easy to get a CORS violation when you've got one of these in the mix.
			</p>
		</section>
		<section>
			<p>
				I got a reply from my friend Lawrence Kincheloe.
				He gave me permission to publish his reply.
				Here it is:
				<blockquote>
					<section>
